4. To start all thing i must need to create production plan or not ?

‚öôÔ∏è Let‚Äôs Compare Both Approaches


üîπ Option 1: With Production Plan (Large-Scale / Planned Manufacturing)

Use this when:
- You have many Sales Orders or products to plan at once.
- You want to analyze stock and auto-create multiple Work Orders together.
- You need a production manager‚Äôs planning view (capacity, deadlines, etc.).
- You do batch production (not just one product at a time).

flow :

Sales Orders / Forecast
      ‚Üì
Production Plan
      ‚Üì
Auto-creates multiple Work Orders
      ‚Üì
Each Work Order ‚Üí BOM + Routing ‚Üí Job Cards ‚Üí Stock Entries




‚úÖ Advantages:
- Great for large factories or make-to-stock manufacturing.
- Automatically handles multiple items.
- Checks material availability before creating Work Orders.
- Reduces manual Work Order creation.

‚ö†Ô∏è Downside:
- Slightly more setup and an extra step before Work Orders.
- Not ideal for small or fast, single-item jobs.



Option 2: Without Production Plan (Simple / On-Demand Manufacturing)

Use this when:
- You‚Äôre a small or mid-size setup.
- You only make one or few items at a time.
- You produce on-demand (e.g., based on a single Sales Order).
- You don‚Äôt need aggregated planning or MRP logic.

flow :

Sales Order (or manual trigger)
      ‚Üì
Work Order (create directly) including BOM + Routing(it cintain opearations, workstation details)
     ‚Üì
Material Transfer for Manufacture (Stock Entry)
     ‚Üì
Job Cards (per operation)
     ‚Üì
Stock Entry (Manufacture)
     ‚Üì
Work Order Completed


‚úÖ Advantages:
- Fast and simple ‚Äî fewer steps.
- Great for custom manufacturing or prototyping.
- Easy to control manually.

‚ö†Ô∏è Downside:
- No automatic material shortage visibility across multiple products.
- You have to manage Work Orders individually.


üí¨ Simple Rule to Remember:
Production Plan = Planning tool (optional)
Work Order = Execution tool (mandatory)



